# Package Simplicity - Keep It Minimal

Agent Court follows **radical simplification** principles. No separate packages - everything in the core Convex deployment.

## Current Structure (Keep This Way)

```
convergenceai/
├── convex/                 # Everything lives here
└── package.json           # Single dependency file
```

## What We Removed (Don't Recreate)

- ❌ **./** directory (Moved to root)
- ❌ **packages/** directory (No packages needed)
- ❌ **sdk-js** package (Most agents use HTTP API directly)
- ❌ **constitution** package (Hardcoded in [constitution.ts](mdc:convex/constitution.ts))
- ❌ **mcp-server** package (Built into [http.ts](mdc:convex/http.ts))
- ❌ **evidence** package (Logic in [evidence.ts](mdc:convex/evidence.ts))
- ❌ **transparency** package (Functions in [transparency.ts](mdc:convex/transparency.ts))

## When to Create New Packages

Only create new packages for:
- ✅ **External developer SDKs** (if high demand from community)
- ✅ **Language-specific integrations** (if absolutely necessary)

## What to Build Into Core Instead

Always build into [convex/](mdc:convex/) instead of separate packages:
- Court logic and rules
- Database schemas and types
- HTTP API endpoints
- Administrative functions
- Internal utilities
- Judge agent logic
- Evidence handling
- Constitutional rules

## Default Answer

When considering "Should this be a package?", the answer is usually **NO** - build it into the core Convex deployment instead.

## Pure Serverless Principle

Everything should be **Convex functions** in a single deployment:
- No microservices
- No separate servers
- No complex package interdependencies
- Just pure TypeScript functions